UID:Tle2hWiy5CLmKyGPbNR7H
SUMMARY:Efficient Automatic Data Placement for GPU and CPU Tiered Memory Sy
	stems
DTSTAMP:20260620T130333Z
DTSTART:20260625T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Ziyi Zhao  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis Defense
	  Department: Computer Science  Location: Duncan Hall 3076  Modern applica
	tions\, from AI and machine learning (ML) to large-scale analytics\, are i
	ncreasingly data-intensive\, and their performance depends on how fast the
	y can access their data. They run on GPUs and CPUs that access that data i
	n memory\, and that memory consists of different kinds\, so it forms tiers
	: fast but small on top\, large but slow below. So where these programs' d
	ata sits in this hierarchy directly shapes how fast they run. But the fast
	 tier is far too small to hold all the data they touch\; only a small frac
	tion is worth keeping there\, and that fraction changes from phase to phas
	e. Every page moved up forces another down\, so the problem is to decide w
	hich data is worth more in the fast tier than the data it would displace\,
	 constantly as the workload runs.  Making these decisions automatically is
	 crucial but challenging. The operating system has only a coarse\, indirec
	t view of how a program accesses memory\, so it must infer which data is h
	ot\; and acting on that inference is a trade-off\, since the gain from bet
	ter placement must outweigh the cost of the move. The key is an adaptive p
	olicy: one that turns the coarse access signal into data-movement decision
	s and refines itself from their feedback\, learning the right placement fo
	r each workload as it runs.  This thesis realizes such policies to achieve
	 efficient data placement across three tiered-memory settings in modern sy
	stems. On the GPU\, where a fast high-bandwidth memory is backed by a larg
	e\, slower host memory\, hardware access counters with an adaptive thresho
	ld and robust host-side management migrate hot data without thrashing\, ru
	nning 3 to 4x faster than the default placement on ML training and inferen
	ce workloads. On the CPU\, the counter-driven\, adaptive placement extends
	 to local and CXL memory. And across persistent memory and disk\, the syst
	em moves data in a way that is resilient to power failures\, improving sys
	tem-wide performance by 1.7x. In all three settings\, the policies are sel
	f-tuning\, require no application changes\, and generalize across AI\, ML\
	, and HPC workloads\, leading in performance among OS-level approaches.htt
	ps://riceuniversity.zoom.us/j/92921253250?pwd=SKtzuOREw2NqDuaqtW9NqBwFzm85
	fa.1 (https://riceuniversity.zoom.us/j/92921253250?pwd=SKtzuOREw2NqDuaqtW9
	NqBwFzm85fa.1)  (Department : Computer Science)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu
	/live/events/431887-efficient-automatic-data-placement-for-gpu-and-cpu\n\n
	From Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/431887-efficient-automatic-data-pla
	cement-for-gpu-and-cpu
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Duncan Hall
